ciliana\u003C/desc>\n            \u003C/graphic>\n         \u003C/surface>\n    \u003C/facsimile>\n    \u003Ctext>\n        \u003Cbody>\n            \u003Cdiv type=\"edition\" xml:space=\"preserve\" xml:lang=\"grc\" resp=\"#VM\">\n                \u003Cab>\n                    \u003Clb n=\"1\"/>Ε\u003Cunclear>ἰ\u003C/unclear>βέ\n                    \u003Clb n=\"2\"/>λο̄\n                \u003C/ab>\n            \u003C/div>\n            \u003Cdiv type=\"apparatus\">\n                \u003ClistApp>\n                    \u003Capp>\n                        \u003Cnote>Text after Nenci 1995\u003C/note> \u003C!-- check edition -->\n                    \u003C/app>\n                \u003C/listApp>\n            \u003C/div>\n            \u003Cdiv type=\"translation\">\n                \u003Cp>\u003C!--translation(s) - add @xml:lang for 'en' or 'it' to div-->\u003C/p>\n            \u003C/div>\n            \u003Cdiv type=\"commentary\">\n                \u003Cp>\u003C!--commented out pending revision-->\n                    \u003C!--large block, with inscr. on upper part. Block shows signs of later re-use. Simply bears name, 'Eibelos' (in genitive: eibelo). N points out that this name is not otherwise attested, and 'potrebbe essere caratteristico dell'area elima'; moreover, the closest analogy is actually Eielos in Entella V.3 and VIII.3-4; 'non si puo\\ qui non ricordare che l'alfabeto greco penetra ad Entella da Selinunte e che l'antroponimo Nanos di una iscrizione funeraria entellina della fine del VI-inizio V sec. a.C. trova riscontro nel Nannelaios o meglio Nanelaios di una nota defixio selinuntina'. (Entella inscr. is Nenci, Novita..., in Atti delle Seconde Gionate...elima, 1994.-->\u003C/p>\n            \u003C/div>\n            \u003Cdiv type=\"bibliography\">\n                \u003ClistBibl type=\"edition\">\n                    \u003Cbibl type=\"bulletin\" n=\"SEG\">\n                        \u003CcitedRange>56.1100\u003C/citedRange>\n                        \u003Cptr ta